    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "Once clue to what is going on is that if <code>e</code> is <code>null</code>, then <code>e instanceof XYZ</code> will be <code>false</code>, regardless of what <code>XYZ</code> is. In other words, you did not catch <code>null</code>; you caught an actual instance of <code>NullPointerException</code>. As to <i>&quot;why else would anyone <code>throw null</code>&quot;</i> -- one might do it inadvertently (as in <code>throw this.lastException();</code> where <code>lastException()</code> returns <code>null</code>.) Re &quot;Fun fact&quot; -- I guess IntelliJ isn&#39;t so intelli. File a bug report!"
